ng .skill files (ZIP format with SKILL.md inside)\n   - Created updated qemu-validate.skill with build_libnn.sh + run_qemu_test.sh as primary workflow\n   - Created updated fpga-bench.skill with build_libnn.sh + run_fpga_test.sh as primary workflow\n   - Preserved compare_perf.py from old fpga-bench.skill\n\nNow for the optimization explanation the user wants in the summary:\n\nThe optimization targets the case where `out_tensor_ch` is small (≤64). The original tiling GEMM uses `vqmacc` which vectorizes across output channels (col2 dimension). When out_tensor_ch=16 and VLEN=1024, the vector register can hold 128 i8 elements but only 16 are used = 87.5% waste (or 93.75% for the 1024-bit context).\n\nThe vd4dots approach instead vectorizes along the reduction dimension (col = in_ch × ker_h × ker_w), which is typically much larger (e.g., 3×3×16 = 144). With VLEN=1024 and LMUL=M8, you get 1024 bytes per vector operation. The `vd4dots` instruction does 4-element dot products, processing 4 bytes at once into 32-bit accumulators.\n\nThe `nn_mat_mult_kernel_s8_offset_v2` processes 2 output channels × 2 output pixels per iteration, using LMUL=M4 for the vd4dots, which fills the vector registers well along the reduction dimension.\n\nThis gives 2.49x cycle speedup because:\n- Vector utilization goes from ~6.25% (16/256 elements in LMUL=M2) to near 100% along the reduction axis\n- Fewer total vector operations needed\n- Better memory access patterns (sequential weight access per channel)\n\nThe instruction count reduction is even more dramatic: 3.68x (3,826,922 → 1,039,912), showing the algorithm does fundamentally less work by better utilizing wide vectors.\n</analysis>\n\n<summary>\n1. Primary Request and Intent:\n   - **Original goal (from prior conversation)**: Pick the most profitable libnn function to optimize, rewrite with RVV, verify via QEMU, benchmark on FPGA\n   - **This conversation**: Apply /simplify review fixes to the optimized code and scripts, re-verify correctness via the 3-script pipeline (build → QEMU → FPGA), then update the `.skill` files for builder/QEMU/FPGA runners to reference the new reusable scripts\n   - User also asked how correctness is tested — answer: existing unit tests in `Examples/unit_func/t_*.c` compare function output against pre-computed golden data in `Examples/unit_func/bin/*.bin`, printing \"accuracy checking pass/fail\"\n\n2. Key Technical Concepts:\n   - **libnn**: Andes Neural Network Library for RISC-V with multi-variant implementations (plain C, DSP, RVV)\n   - **AX45MPV target**: RV64 with VLEN=1024, RVV 1.0, vd4dots support\n   - **The Optimization — Why 2.49x Speedup**:\n     - The target function `conv_HWC_s8_s8_s8_asym_bias_any` uses im2col + GEMM for convolution\n     - The **original tiling GEMM** vectorizes across output channels (`out_tensor_ch` = col2 dimension) using `vqmacc`. When `out_tensor_ch=16` and VLEN=1024, the vector register holds 128 i8 elements but only 16 are used — **87.5% vector capacity wasted**\n     - The **new vd4dots path** vectorizes along the **reduction dimension** (col = `in_ch × ker_h × ker_w`, typically 144+). With VLEN=1024 and LMUL=M8, each vector operation processes up to 1024 bytes — **near 100% vector utilization**\n     - `nn_mat_mult_kernel_s8_offset_v2` processes 2 output channels × 2 output pixels per iteration using LMUL=M4 vd4dots, which does 4-element dot products (4 i8 → 1 i32 accumulate)\n     - Dispatch condition: `out_tensor_ch <= 64` routes to vd4dots path; larger channel counts keep the original tiling GEMM which works well when col2 is large enough to fill vectors\n     - **Result**: 5,456,391 → 2,187,394 cycles (**2.49x speedup**), 3,826,922 → 1,039,912 instructions (**3.68x reduction**)\n   - **QEMU semihosting quirk**: In Claude Code sandbox, QEMU writes semihosting output to fd 9 (not stdout), requiring `strace -f -e trace=write` to capture\n   - **FPGA board testing**: GDB+ICE via expect script, `-mvh` for semihosting, `-DGETENV_TESTDIR` for golden data path resolution\n   - **Skill files**: ZIP archives containing `<name>/SKILL.md` (and optional scripts), used by Claude Code for task-specific knowledge\n\n3. Files and Code Sections:\n   - **`Source/ConvolutionFunctions/riscv_nn_conv_HWC_s8_s8_s8_asym_bias_any.c`**\n     - THE main optimized file. Lines 457-601 contain the new vd4dots dispatch path\n     - /simplify fixes applied in this conversation:\n       1. Removed dead code `pWt += 0;` (was line 564), replaced with comment\n       2. Pre-computed im2col kernel bounds to avoid redundant multiplication:\n     ```c\n     // BEFORE (redundant multiplication in inner loop):\n     for (long cur_ker_y = cur_out_y * stride_y - pad_y; cur_ker_y < cur_out_y * stride_y - pad_y + ker_dim_y; cur_ker_y++)\n     \n     // AFTER (pre-computed):\n     const long ker_y_start = cur_out_y * stride_y - pad_y;\n     const long ker_y_end = ker_y_start + ker_dim_y;\n     for (long cur_ker_y = ker_y_start; cur_ker_y < ker_y_end; cur_ker_y++)\n     ```\n     - The optimization adds an if/else at line 461: `if (out_tensor_ch <= 64)` dispatches to vd4dots path using `nn_mat_mult_kernel_s8_offset_v2` with 2-column im2col batching; else uses original tiling GEMM\n\n   - **`qemu-validate/build_libnn.sh`** (66 lines)\n     - Standalone library build script, parameters: `--cpu NAME`, `--vec-cfg CFG`, `--verbose`\n     - Defaults: ax45mpv, zve64d toolchain\n\n   - **`qemu-validate/run_qemu_test.sh`** (~189 lines)\n     - QEMU test runner with strace mode for semihosting capture\n     - Parameters: `--vlen N`, `--strace`, `--perf`, `--timeout N`\n\n   - **`qemu-validate/run_fpga_test.sh`** (~190 lines)\n     - FPGA benchmark runner via GDB/ICEman\n     - /simplify fixes applied:\n       1. Changed `-mext-vector` to `-mext-vector=zve64d` for consistency with other scripts\n       2. Changed `OUTPUT=$(\"${BOARD_WRAPPER}\" \"${TEST_ADX}\" 2>&1)` + `EXIT_CODE=$?` to `OUTPUT=$(\"${BOARD_WRAPPER}\" \"${TEST_ADX}\" 2>&1) || tr